Kowloon's presence in the Great Northern Forest is strongest in the northern crown and checkpoint rings. The Jade Magistracy's Wardens of Iron maintain a rotating garrison at the northern customs post, staffed on seasonal rotation — no single commander holds the post for more than one season. The Courier Lantern Office operates signal relay stations in the northern crown. Waystations in Kowloon's influence zone use strict inventory chalkboards, sealed ration lockers, and covenant plaques. Dispute circles use witness stones mirroring Kowloon's public-judgment ethic. Kowloon's founding House Jien's scribal methods descend from the same measurement tradition that produced the forest's witness-judgment arbitration system. The Oath-Crossing negotiation was contentious: Kowloon's envoys demanded binding arbitration clauses enforceable by the Jade Magistracy; Midgaard's wardens refused single-city jurisdiction over neutral ground. The Cairn-Keeper elder Toreth Gael's compromise — witness judgment at standing stones, verdicts carved into stone rather than filed in either city's courts — became the warden tribunal system still practiced at the Oath-Crossing stones. Kowloon's northern patrol captains record incidents in duplicate: one ledger for Kowloon, one for shared forest archives.

