Kiess has no formal presence in the Great Northern Forest — the forest lies between Midgaard and Kowloon, well east of Kiess's position on Roc Road. Kiess Trade Syndics receive Lantern Road status reports from Midgaard road warden channels, treating northern forest conditions as a factor in eastern trade timing. The forest's joint-commission governance model — neither city claims sole authority, disputes go to neutral witness judgment — is viewed positively by Kiess as an example of institutional design that prevents either city from using road control as political leverage. By contrast, Roc Road's dual-authority problem (Midgaard claims charter sovereignty, Kiess controls effective throughput) lacks the forest road's clean neutral-ground framework, which Kiess convoy marshals cite as a persistent source of jurisdictional friction.

