Rivennid ecological understanding of the Great Northern Forest identifies it as a partially intact ancient root-network ecosystem operating under sustained human pressure. The Verdant Depths at the forest's northern heart are the oldest and most ecologically coherent zone; the surrounding buffer zone — including what became the Forest of Confusion to the northwest — was the managed outer margin of the same root-connected system. The Everkeepers' planting-rings were the only human infrastructure compatible with the root network's autonomous ecological cycles because they added to the network rather than managing it. The Lantern Road, built using the Bent Mile Principle, is also ecologically compatible in principle — it yields to terrain rather than cutting through ecologically significant zones. Rivennid in Midgaard track the Thornwood substrate crystal formation as an existential concern: the failing binding is already affecting root-network behavior in the estate-forest's margins, and if the crystal substrate's responsive behavior fully destabilizes, the effect on the nearby root network segments is not predictable from any current ecological model.

