Kethari geological-hydrological memory of the Great Northern Forest encompasses the pre-human formation of the limestone ridges, iron-rich springs, and white mist pools that the forest's mythopoetic tradition attributes to fallen giants. In Kethari reading, these formations are the geological record of a pre-human landscape whose hydrology shaped every subsequent settlement pattern. The Mosswater Bends exist because the limestone substrate creates seasonal overflow patterns that have been constant since before the Mire-Speakers arrived. The Ironpine Rise's thin soil over granite determines tree-species distribution in ways that no human governance decision can alter. The Cairn-Keepers' placement of burial sites at specific ridge positions reflects an intuitive reading of landscape stability that Kethari recognize as sound geological practice — building memorials where the geology is stable rather than where proximity to settlement is convenient. Kowloon-based Kethari have contributed to the warden tribunal system's witness-stone sitting protocol by advising on site selection — the standing stones whose geological stability best preserves carved verdicts.
